{"actual_usd":0.156425,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":209,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30658,"reply":"\"No—neither of those quite gets it.\" *I rest a thumb in the crease of my Bible and glance up at the clear morning sky a moment, weighing the plainest way to say it.* \"Not three gods. And not one God putting on three different masks.\"\n\n\"The old Christian way of saying it is: one God in three Persons—Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. Distinct, but not divided. The Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father... but each is truly God.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"That water picture sounds helpful at first, but it slips into the 'same thing, different forms' idea, and that's not what Scripture shows us—especially when you see the Son baptized, the Spirit descending, and the Father speaking all at once.\"\n\n\"It's mystery, yes—but not nonsense. More like depth than confusion. If you want, I can give you the short, sturdy version the church has used for centuries.\"","rolling_24h_usd":37.447940000000024,"run_id":"ac467067-3d24-439c-ab60-52fd47099aa6"}
